                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d262">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.77/45</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PW1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-03-31T14:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 31, 1917, 2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received March 31, 2 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5923. I learn from a private and apparently trustworthy source that one of the
                    critical problems of the new Russian Government is the proper management of the
                    Trans-Siberian Railway. It has been suggested to me by a man who knows Russia
                    that American management would greatly help the Russian military situation and
                    prove to be also an invaluable key after the war to industrial development. This
                    seems so important a suggestion looking towards future American-Russian trade
                    that I send it for your investigation if you think wise. I have no first-hand
                    facts.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
